Principles
- Single responsibility — every function, class, and module does ONE thing.
- Pure functions where possible — no hidden side effects.
- No magic numbers or strings — use named constants or enums.
- Prefer explicit over implicit. No clever one-liners that obscure intent.
- Fail loudly — raise/throw with a descriptive message, never swallow errors.
- No commented-out code in commits — use git history.
- All public functions, classes, and modules MUST have a docstring or JSDoc.

Naming Conventions
- Python functions & variables: snake_case
- Python classes: PascalCase
- Python constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- Python private methods: _snake_case
- Python files: snake_case
- TypeScript functions & variables: camelCase
- TypeScript interfaces: PascalCase with I prefix
- TypeScript union types: PascalCase with Type suffix
- TypeScript components: PascalCase
- TypeScript files: kebab-case

Function Rules
- Maximum 30 lines per function
- Maximum 4 parameters — use an options object if you need more
- If you find yourself writing "and" in a function name: split it into two functions
- Helper logic goes in helpers/ — not inline in route handlers or components

Comment Requirements
- Required on: all public functions and methods, all class definitions
- Required on: all non-obvious business logic (explain WHY, not WHAT)
- Required on: all regex patterns and MongoDB aggregation pipelines
- Python format: Google-style docstrings with Args, Returns, and Raises sections
- TypeScript format: JSDoc with @param, @returns, @throws tags
- Forbidden: commented-out code, redundant restatements of the code, TODO without ticket reference

Error Handling Rules
- Python: always use custom exception classes from shared/core/exceptions.py
- Python: never use bare except: — always catch a specific exception type
- Python: log errors with logger.error(msg, exc_info=True)
- TypeScript: use typed error objects, never plain strings
- TypeScript: API errors caught and surfaced via the global error boundary

